{{Infobox museum | name = The Contemporary | native_name = | native_name_lang = | logo = Logo of The Contemporary, Baltimore.png | logo_upright = | logo_alt = | logo_caption = | image = | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | map_type = | map_relief = | map_size = | map_caption = | coordinates = {{Coord|39.2964|N|76.6179|W|region:US-MD_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | former_name = Contemporary Museum | established = 1989 | dissolved = 2012; re-established 2013 | location = [[Baltimore, Maryland]] | type = [[wikt:peripatetic|peripatetic]] | accreditation = | key_holdings = none | collections = none | collection_size = | visitors = | founder = George Ciscle | executive_director = | leader_type = | leader = | director = | president = | ceo = | chairperson = | curator = | architect = | historian = | owner = | network = | website = {{url|contemporary.org}} | embedded = }}
'''The Contemporary''' is an itinerant museum of [[contemporary art]] in [[Baltimore, Maryland]], in the United States. It does not collect artworks. It was started as the '''Contemporary Museum''' by George Ciscle in 1989. During its first decade, it had no fixed home, but instead was "dedicated to redefining the concept of the museum". It sponsored exhibitions in a variety of non-traditional spaces around Baltimore,<ref>Stein, Judith E. "Sins of Omission." Art in America. October 1993. p. 112.</ref> as well as borrowing space in partnering institutions such as the [[Baltimore Museum of Art]], [[Maryland Historical Society]], [[Peabody Conservatory]] and [[Walters Art Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contemporary.org/about.html|title=About Us|publisher=Contemporary Museum|accessdate=August 12, 2011}}</ref>
In 1999, the Contemporary Museum moved to 100 W. Centre Street, one block from the Walters, in the [[Mount Vernon, Baltimore|Mount Vernon]] neighborhood of downtown Baltimore, where it organized exhibitions and related programming for nearly ten years. In 2011, the museum moved out of the W. Centre Street space and organized projects in neighboring institutions and buildings.
The museum suspended operations in 2012,<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20130628170512/http://contemporary.org/ Contemporary Museum Baltimore, accessed 06/28/2013</ref> but in September 2013 announced that it would re-open under a new name, The Contemporary, after a year spent "reimagining the organization's mission, vision and operating structure".<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20130907115419/http://www.contemporary.org/ The Contemporary, accessed 09/07/2013</ref>
